Answer A Text: \( 2 \)
Answer B Text: \( 1 \)
Answer C Text: \( -2 \)
Answer D Text: \( \frac{1}{2} \)

question:
Question Text: These two shapes are similar (not drawn to scale). What should replace the star?
Question Image: Two scalene triangles. The bigger one has sides 9 cm and 7.5 cm. On the smaller triangle, the side corresponding to the 9 cm is 6 cm, and the side corresponding to the 7.5 cm is marked with a star.
Answer A Text: \( 3.75 \mathrm{~cm} \)
Answer B Text: \( 5 \mathrm{~cm} \)
Answer C Text: \( 4.5 \mathrm{~cm} \)
Answer D Text: Not enough information
turns: [{'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'Do you remember what "similar" means in math?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'It means they are related in some way'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'It means that corresponding angles are congruent, meaning they are the same, and the sides have increased by a scale factor, or a multiplier. So we have to figure out what we would multiply 9 by to get 6.  That will be our scale factor.  Then we can multiply 7.5 by that scale factor to find the missing side. We can do that several ways, but I like to set up ratios.  If I put x/6 = 7.5/9, then I can use cross multiplication, or cross products.  Have you ever done that before?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'I dont kno'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': "That's okay.  Another thing we can do is just use division.  I know that 9 x ? = 6, so I can take 6 divided by 9 to find the missing scale factor. Now the ? in this situation is my scale factor."}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'Hello?'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': "I'm here.  Did you see my last two responses?"}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'Yes'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'We are finding the scale factor by taking 6 divided by 9.  What did you get?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'I dont know how to do it'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'Do you have a calculator handy?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'Yes'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'Great!  take 6 divided by 9 for me please.'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': '0.66666666666666667'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'Excellent.  What that number, .667 means for us is that smaller triangle is .667 times the size of the larger one.  So, what we need to do is take 7.5 x .666666667 to find that missing side.'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'The answer is 5'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'Yes!  Very good.'}]

question:
Question Text: Leo and Clara are arguing equivalent fractions. Leo says \( \frac{9}{15}=\frac{12}{20} \) Clara says \( \frac{9}{15}=\frac{15}{21} \) Who is correct?
Answer A Text: Only Leo
Answer B Text: Only Clara
Answer C Text: Both Leo and Clara
Answer D Text: Neither is correct
turns: [{'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'Hello Sophia :). How can I help you today?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': "I don't know which child is right. Could you help me work it ou?"}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'Absolutely can do ğŸ‘. So for this question what would be useful is to simplify the fractions... Do you know what 9/15 simplified would be? Is there a number we can divide both 9 and 15 by?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': "yes, it's 3"}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'ExcellentğŸ‰ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ğŸ‰. 9/15 is 3/5 :). Lets do the same for 12/20. Lets simplify 15/21?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': '5 sevenths'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'Amazing, is that the same as 3/5?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'Nope'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'Fantastic Sophia so Clara is not correct. question:
Question Text: The following formula can convert temperatures from Celsius, \( C \), to Fahrenheit, \( F \).
Question Text: \( C=\frac{5}{9}(F-32) \)
Question Text: Which would be a possible first step to make \( F \) the subject?
Answer A Text: Add \( 32 \)
Answer B Text: Divide by \( 5 \)
Answer C Text: Subtract \( 9 \)
Answer D Text: Divide by \( 9 \)
turns: [{'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'Hi Nina! How are you today?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'im good how are you'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'good thank you! would you like some help with rearranging formulae?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'im stuck on this question. i thought you add 32 both sides'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': "okay! so you won't want to add 32 yet because it is inside the brackets. I always think of these in terms of function machines and then work backwards with it. if F goes in, it is F ==> -32 ==> x 5 ==> divide by 9 ==> C. although the x5 and divide by 9 could be either way around. so if you go backwards, you would either x by 9 first or divide by 5"}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'so it would become. 9C = 5(F-32)'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'good! out of interest, what would happen next?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'expand the brackets?'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'not quite, have a look back at the function machine'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'I dont really use function machine sbecause i dont know what they areğŸ˜…'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': "it's just a flow diagram of the order things happen in :)"}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'would you do + 32. both sides'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'not quite, because the -32 is in the bracket, that means when you are rearranging it will be the last thing to change'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'so then you multiply out the brackets'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': "you don't have to, no. If you have 9C = 5(F-32) you want to get rid of the 5 outside of the bracket"}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'so - 5'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'at the moment the bracket is multiplied by 5, what is the inverse of that?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': '/ 5'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'good! next step you divide by 5'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': '9c / 5 = F - 32'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'good, now final step?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'finally add 32 to get F on its own'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'yes! well done!'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'thanks claire ill give me answers now'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'okay! Have a nice evening!'}]

question:
Question Text: Jack and Lily are discussing the output of this 2-step function machine
Question Image: A function machine with 4 rectangles in a row, joined by arrows pointing from left to right. The first rectangle on the left has "input" written above it and "p" written inside it. The next rectangle has "âˆ’3" written inside it, the next rectangle has "âœ• 2" written inside it and the final rectangle on the right is empty and has "output" written above it.
Question Text: Jack says the output is \( 2(\boldsymbol{p}-\mathbf{3}) \)  Lily says the output is \( \mathbf{2 p - 6} \)  Who is correct?
Answer A Text: Only Jack
Answer B Text: Only Lily
Answer C Text: Both Jack and Lily
Answer D Text: Neither is correct
turns: [{'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'Hi Chijioke - how are you?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'Hi,please can you help me with this question'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'of course. what are you thinking so far?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'P-3Ã—2 on a function machine'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': "great start. so let's look at what that means, in that order"}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'Could it be expanded to 2p-6 or 2(p-3)'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'so are you thinking both Jack and Lila are right?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'Yes'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'why is that?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': "I am not sure of it I guess it might be none of them because 2p-6  can't be the output"}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': "let's go back to the function machine. follow the order like you did before. P - 3 x 2. p-3x2"}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'Could I use bodmas'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': "It has to be in that order. so in words, p take away 3, then multiply by 2. if we look at Jack's answer, 2(p-3)"}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'So would it be 2(p-3'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'how would you describe this in words?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'P take away3 multiply by 2'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'good!! ğŸ‘ so that matches what you said. could Lily be right?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'Maybe no'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'Why?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': "Because 2p -6 isn't the same as p-3x2"}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': "as you said before 2(p-3) can be expanded to 2p-6 but in this question, 2p-6 wouldn't be the output"}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'So could Lily be wrong but Jack is right'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': "I would agree with you here, but we know that Lily's answer is Jack's answer expanded"}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'So are both right'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': "If we go through the function machine, would we get 2p-6 at the end? these questions are designed to make you really think, and you've really done that!"}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'I do not really understand how both answers are right please'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': "follow the function machine... p - 3 x 2. to complete the steps in that order, p-3 must be done first, hence the brackets used in Jack's answer. the output = 2(p-3). we can now expand this output to get 2p - 6, BUT 2p-6 isn't a direct output from what was inputted. It's a confusing one, but I think you are right with Jack"}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'But I wrote that and Jack was correct and i did not get it right'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'so in this case, 2p-6 is another potential answer'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'Okay i get it'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'what answer would you select?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'Both are correct'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'ok good work Chijioke ğŸ˜Š. can i help you with anything else today?'}, {'role': 'student', 'content': 'No thank you'}, {'role': 'tutor', 'content': 'ok - I will send you back to the lesson now - well done. Great deeper thinking going on here'}]

Does that make sense?', 'student': 'So 14?'}, {'turn': 4, 'teacher': "That's the one! Happy to carry on, or anything else I can help with?", 'student': 'Iâ€™m doing homework school and it says plot 3 points on the line y=-4/3x-1 could you help with that'}, {'turn': 5, 'teacher': "Certainly, so that's the same idea as this question. But this time we can pick any values of x. So let's do x = 1 first. Actually, if it's -4/3x it will be easier if we pick a multiple of 3, so let's do x = 6", 'student': 'Ok :)'}, {'turn': 6, 'teacher': '-4/3 times 6?', 'student': 'Iâ€™m not to sure what -4/3 is'}, {'turn': 7, 'teacher': "Ah ok it's negative four thirds so can you find one third of 6? 1/3 of 6?", 'student': '2'}, {'turn': 8, 'teacher': 'Perfect, then 4/3 will be 4 x 2', 'student': '8'}, {'turn': 9, 'teacher': 'Yep and we want -4/3 so...', 'student': '-8?'}, {'turn': 10, 'teacher': "That's it! So -4/3 times 6 is 8, then just - 1 the final answer?", 'student': '47'}, {'turn': 11, 'teacher': 'Sorry that should have been -8 -1, that was my mistake. Question Text: Solve the equation: \( -10=-\frac{p}{5} \)

Answer B Text: \( p=-50 \)
Answer C Text: \( p=50 \)
Answer D Text: \( p=2 \)

Question Text: A snail travels \( 3 \) metres in \( 40 \) minutes  How would you work out its average speed in metres per second?
Answer A Text: \( \frac{3}{40} \div 60 \)
Answer B Text: \( 3 \div 40 \)
Answer C Text: \( \frac{40}{3} \div 60 \)
Answer D Text: \( \frac{3}{40} \times 60 \)

Answer A Text: \( 4: 2 \)
Answer B Text: \( 2: 4 \)
Answer C Text: \( 2: 1 \)
Answer D Text: \( 1: 2 \)
